    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is magnesium glycinate or citrate better for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is generally better for sleep. The glycine amino acid in the chelate crosses the blood-brain barrier and binds to GABA receptors, producing a direct calming effect on the central nervous system. Glycine also lowers core body temperature, which is a critical trigger for sleep onset. A 2012 study in <em>Neuropsychopharmacology</em> found that glycine before bedtime significantly improved subjective sleep quality. Citrate is a solid all-purpose form but lacks the sleep-specific neurological benefits of glycine and can cause GI discomfort at higher doses.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the bioavailability of magnesium glycinate vs citrate?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate has approximately 80% intestinal absorption due to its amino acid chelate structure, which utilizes active transport pathways. Magnesium citrate has approximately 25-30% bioavailability, absorbed primarily through passive diffusion. Both are significantly superior to magnesium oxide at 4%. The higher absorption of glycinate means more magnesium reaches your bloodstream per milligram consumed and less remains in the gut to cause digestive side effects.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take magnesium glycinate and citrate together?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Because glycinate and citrate use different absorption pathways — glycinate through amino acid active transport and citrate through passive diffusion — combining them may improve total magnesium absorption. Ensure your combined supplemental intake does not exceed the Tolerable Upper Intake Level of 350mg per day. Some practitioners recommend glycinate at bedtime for sleep and citrate earlier in the day for general supplementation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does magnesium citrate cause diarrhea?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium citrate can cause loose stools and diarrhea, particularly at doses above 200mg per serving. Unabsorbed magnesium citrate draws water into the intestinal lumen through osmosis, producing a laxative effect. At standard supplementation doses of 150-200mg, most people tolerate it well. If you experience GI discomfort, switch to magnesium glycinate, which has virtually no osmotic laxative effect due to its amino acid transport absorption pathway.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much magnesium glycinate should I take for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Take 200-300mg of elemental magnesium from glycinate 30-60 minutes before bedtime. Start at 200mg for the first week and increase to 300mg if needed. The adult RDA is 310-320mg for women and 400-420mg for men from all sources. Since the average American diet provides about 250mg from food, a 200mg supplement typically brings total intake to the RDA range.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does glycine do for sleep?</summary>
      <p>Glycine is an inhibitory neurotransmitter that lowers core body temperature by dilating peripheral blood vessels, activates GABA-A receptors to calm the nervous system, and enhances serotonin production (the precursor to melatonin). A 2012 study found that 3 grams of glycine before bedtime significantly improved subjective sleep quality and reduced next-day fatigue. In magnesium glycinate, you get both the mineral and amino acid benefits in a single supplement.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is magnesium glycinate safe for long-term use?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is considered one of the safest forms for long-term daily use. The NIH classifies magnesium as having low toxicity risk in people with normal kidney function. Glycinate has the lowest incidence of GI side effects among all magnesium forms. Individuals with kidney disease should consult a physician before supplementing. No adverse effects from long-term glycinate use have been reported at standard doses.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Which magnesium form is best for anxiety?</summary>
      <p>Magnesium glycinate is the preferred form for anxiety. The glycine component acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter, calming the central nervous system by binding to GABA-A and glycine receptors. This dual mechanism — magnesium for nervous system regulation plus glycine for direct anxiolytic effects — makes glycinate uniquely suited for anxiety management. Magnesium L-threonate is another option for anxiety, as it is the only form shown to increase brain magnesium levels.</p>
    </details>

